            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Levi Goldstein was raised across the bay in Alameda, the son of a high school history teacher and a dental hygienist. His childhood was a comfortable but predictable landscape of tree-lined streets and weekend trips to the city. San Francisco, for Levi, was always the goal\u2014a chaotic, vibrant canvas he longed to paint himself onto. He enrolled at the Academy of Art University, fueled by dreams of gallery openings and a life dedicated to abstract expressionism.\n\nFor two years, he subsisted on cheap ramen and the intoxicating energy of the city's art scene. But the pressure mounted. The daunting cost of living and the crushing weight of needing to create something \"important\" slowly eroded his passion. His art felt forced, his future precarious. During a particularly bleak period, scrolling through city job postings, he saw an opening for MUNI cable car operators. On a whim, driven more by a need for stability than genuine interest, he applied.\n\nThe career shift was his life\u2019s great turning point. The physical, demanding work of a gripman became a new kind of art form. Instead of a brush, he learned to handle the grip lever, feeling the tension of the cable running beneath the street like a city's pulse. He became a human anchor, navigating precipitous hills and mastering the rhythmic clang of the bell. The job offered a perspective on San Francisco he\u2019d never had as an artist chasing inspiration; he was now part of its moving, breathing machinery.\n\nToday, Levi lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in Lower Nob Hill, a short bus ride from the Powell Street cable car barn. His routine is dictated by early shifts and the tides of tourists. After work, he unwinds not by painting, but by sketching in a leather-bound book\u2014portraits of passengers, foggy cityscapes from his route, the mechanical intricacies of the turntable. The pressure is gone; art is for him again. His social life is a small circle of fellow MUNI workers and a couple of old art school friends who admire his unconventional path. Levi's dream is no longer a SoMa gallery show, but to master his craft, maybe win the annual bell-ringing competition, and find a quiet, lasting contentment in the city he serves every day."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHis last night in the Polk Gulch studio, aged 20. The air, thick with turpentine and failure, felt suffocating. A single, muddy-brown canvas sat half-finished on the easel, mocking him. He wasn\u2019t creating art; he was manufacturing anxiety. Packing his few brushes into a cardboard box, he felt not sadness, but a hollow, bone-deep relief. The dream he\u2019d chased across the bay had died. That night, shutting the door on his old life, he first learned that surrender could sometimes feel like freedom.\n\n2.\nHis first solo run on the Powell-Hyde line, a month after being hired. His palms were slick on the cold metal grip lever. Ascending the steep hill past Lombard, a wave of pure terror crested, followed by a profound sense of control. As he felt the rhythmic shudder and pull of the sub-street cable, he realized it wasn't just machinery. It was a current, the city\u2019s very heartbeat, and he was the one guiding it. For the first time, he felt essential, not just ornamental.\n\n3.\nTwo years ago, he spotted Julia, his sharpest critic from art school, clinging to an outside pole on his car near Fisherman's Wharf. She looked up, recognized him, and her jaw dropped. He saw her take in his uniform, the confident way he worked the bell. He gave a simple, professional nod. In that flash of recognition, Levi felt a surge of quiet pride, not shame. His life wasn\u2019t a failure to be explained away, but a new composition she couldn't possibly understand.\n\n4.\nIt was a 5 AM shift last winter. The fog was so thick at California and Powell that the world dissolved into a soft, grey abstraction. He was ringing the bell, its brassy clang cutting through the silence, a sound just for him and the sleeping city. He watched the streetlights bloom like pale, fuzzy flowers in the mist. It was a perfect composition he no longer felt the desperate need to capture on canvas, only to experience. This was his gallery now.\n\n5.\nStanding in Union Square for the annual bell-ringing competition last summer. He wasn\u2019t competing, just watching. He saw the focus in a veteran gripman\u2019s eyes, the way his complex rhythm was less a performance and more a conversation with the bell itself. When he won, the crowd of MUNI families erupted. Levi felt not envy, but a deep sense of belonging and a new, clearer ambition. It wasn't about a gallery opening anymore; it was about earning the right to create that sound."
